notesStmt.note: Title and attribution of translator supplied by cataloger (Zacour-Hirsch).
Incipit (f. 1r): Omnes homines natura scire desiderant. Signum autem est...
Incipit (f. 94r): Omnes homines natura scire desiderant. Nam quaelibet res ferente natura appetit perfectionem ...
Same commentary as UPenn Ms. Codex 764 (Zacour-Hirsch).

msIdentifier.repository: Kislak Center for Special Collections, Rare Books and Manuscripts

msContents.summary: Translation of Aristotle's Metaphysics into Latin by Guilelmus of Moerbeke, with an anonymous commentary and an index to the Metaphysics.

supportDesc.extent: 185 leaves : 291 x 218 (187 x 119) mm. bound to 314 x 222 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Paper, 185; [1-185]; modern foliation in pencil, upper right recto.

layoutDesc.layout: Written in 31 long lines; ruled in lead.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in a Gothic cursive script by a single hand, with marginal and interlinear annotations in a second hand.

decoDesc.decoNote: Rubricated headings, capitals, paragraph marks, and underlining; several manicules (for example, f. 62r, 63r, 54r).

binding.p: Contemporary stamped half calf over wooden boards, with 2 ornamented clasps.

origin.p: Written in Germany in the 15th century (Zacour-Hirsch).
